Using rip3api.ppu

Uses rip3api;

Var RIP : TRIPEngine;
Begin
RIP := TRIPEngine.Create;

// Switch to 24-bit true color mode
RIP.SetPixelFormat(RIP_PIXFMT_RGB24);

// Draw with RGB colors
Var RGB : TRIPRGB;
RGB.R := 255; RGB.G := 128; RGB.B := 0;
RIP.SetColorRGB(RGB);
RIP.OutTextXY(50, 100, 'Hello RIP v3!');

// Or use indexed colors (backward compatible)
RIP.SetColor(14);
RIP.Line(0, 0, 639, 349);

// Export to 24-bit BMP (native in RGB modes)
RIP.SaveBMP('output.bmp');

RIP.Free;
End.

Compile with:  ppcx64 -Mdelphi -Fu<path-to-mystic_ripapi3> -Fu<path-to-mystic_ripapi3>/img -Fu<path-to-mystic_ripapi3>/wav -Fu<path-to-mystic_ripapi3>/pasjpeg yourprogram.pas
No -Fumdl or -Fumystic needed. The unit is fully standalone.

NOTE: The engine uses {$H-} (short strings) to avoid BUG-029.
Classes/TStream require {$H+} and are incompatible. All file I/O
uses Assign/Reset/BlockRead instead of TStream/TFileStream.
Decoders (pasjpeg, wav) follow the same convention.

1. CONSTANTS

Screen Dimensions
RIP_MAX_X          = 639
RIP_MAX_Y          = 349
RIP_MAX_COLORS     = 16

Limits
RIP_MAX_MOUSE      = 128
RIP_MAX_BUTTONS    = 64
RIP_MAX_POLY       = 512
RIP_MAX_VARS       = 64
RIP_MAX_CHR_CHARS  = 256
RIP_MAX_STROKES    = 16384

Fill Styles (BGI)         Line Styles (BGI)
0  EMPTY                  0  SOLID
1  SOLID                  1  DOTTED  ($CCCC)
2  LINE                   2  CENTER  ($FC78)
3  LTSLASH                3  DASHED  ($F8F8)
4  SLASH                  4  USER (16-bit)
5  BKSLASH
6  LTBKSLASH            Write Modes
7  HATCH                  0  COPY_PUT
8  XHATCH                1  XOR_PUT
9  INTERLEAVE             2  AND_PUT  (v3.0)
10 WIDEDOT                3  OR_PUT   (v3.0)  Fonts
11 CLOSEDOT               4  NOT_PUT  (v3.0)    0  DEFAULT (8x8 bitmap)
12 USER (8x8)             1  TRIPLEX    2  SMALL
3  SANSSERIF  4  GOTHIC

EGA_RGB : Array[0..15] of TRIPRgb
Standard EGA hardware RGB values for true-color rendering.

2. TYPES

TRIPColor        = Byte (0..15)
TRIPPoint        = Record { X, Y : SmallInt }
TRIPPalette      = Array[0..15] of Byte
TRIPFillPattern  = Array[0..7] of Byte
TRIPRgb          = Record { R, G, B : Byte }

TRIPMouseField   = Record
Active  : Boolean          Field is active
X0, Y0  : SmallInt         Top-left corner
X1, Y1  : SmallInt         Bottom-right corner
HostCmd : String[80]       Command sent to host on click
Text    : String[80]       Status bar text
Invert  : Boolean          Invert on click

TRIPVariable     = Record
Active   : Boolean         Variable is defined
Name     : String[12]      Identifier (1-12 alphanumeric)
Value    : String[255]     Current value
Persist  : Boolean         Save to database
Required : Boolean         Cannot be blank

TRIPFileQueryResult = Record
Exists : Boolean           File was found
Size   : LongInt           File size in bytes
Date   : String[10]        Date (mode 3)
Time   : String[8]         Time (mode 3)

TRIPButtonStyle  = Record
Width, Height, Orient, Flags, BevelSize,
DFore, DBack, BRight, DDark, Surface,
GrpID, Flags2, ULineCol, CornerCol

TRIPStroke       = Record { Op: Byte; X, Y: SmallInt }
CHR stroke command: 0=end, 1=move, 2=draw

TRIPCHRFont      = Record
Loaded, Name, FirstChar, NumChars,
OrgToCap, OrgToBase, OrgToDec,
Widths[0..255], Offsets[0..255],
Strokes[0..16383], NumStrokes

TRIPPixelBuffer  = Array[0..1023, 0..1279] of Byte
PRIPPixelBuffer  = ^TRIPPixelBuffer

v3.0 Phase 15 — True Color Types:
TRIPRGB          = Record { R, G, B : Byte }  (alias: TRIPRgb)
TRIPRGBA         = Record { R, G, B, A : Byte }
TRIPPixelBufferRGB  = Array[0..1023, 0..1279] of TRIPRGB
PRIPPixelBufferRGB  = ^TRIPPixelBufferRGB
TRIPPixelBufferRGB32 = Array[0..1023, 0..1279] of TRIPRGBA
PRIPPixelBufferRGB32 = ^TRIPPixelBufferRGB32

Pixel Format Constants:
RIP_PIXFMT_INDEXED8 = 0    8-bit indexed (default, v1.54/v2.0 compat)
RIP_PIXFMT_RGB24    = 1    24-bit true color, 3 bytes/pixel
RIP_PIXFMT_RGB32    = 2    32-bit TrueColor, 4 bytes/pixel

3. TRIPEngine CLASS — PUBLIC API

Public Data:
Pixels     : PRIPPixelBuffer      — indexed pixel buffer. Pixels^[Y, X]
PixelsRGB  : PRIPPixelBufferRGB   — 24-bit RGB pixel buffer (v3.0)
PixelsRGB32: PRIPPixelBufferRGB32 — 32-bit RGBA pixel buffer (v3.0)

3.1  Constructor / Destructor

Constructor Create
Allocates the 640x350 pixel buffer (224,000 bytes on heap).
Initializes all 10 CHR font slots to Nil.
Initializes all 10 saved screen slots to Nil.
Sets clipboard to Nil.
Calls Reset to set default state.
After Create, the engine is ready to accept commands.

Destructor Destroy
Frees all loaded CHR fonts (Dispose on non-Nil slots).
Frees all saved screens (Dispose on non-Nil slots).
Frees clipboard (FreeMem if non-Nil).
Frees the pixel buffer.
Call Free (not Destroy directly) per standard Pascal convention.

3.2  RIP Command Processing

Procedure ProcessLine (Line: String)
Feed a line of RIP data. Handles backslash (\) line continuation.
Extracts all !| (and #1|, #2|) command sequences and dispatches
each one through ProcessCommand. Non-RIP text is ignored.

Procedure ProcessCommand (Cmd: String)
Process a single RIP command (the text after !|). Parses level
digit(s) and command character, dispatches to Level 0, 1, or 9.

3.3  Screen Management

Procedure Reset
Restores all state to defaults:
Position: (0,0)
Draw color: 15 (white), fill color: 0 (black)
Fill style: solid, line style: solid, line thickness: 1
Write mode: copy (overwrite)
Font: default 8x8, size 1, horizontal, left/top justify
Text window: (0,0)-(79,42), size 0
Viewport: (0,0)-(639,349)
Palette: default EGA 16-color
Fill pattern: all $FF (solid)
Button style: BevelSize=1, DFore=15, BRight=15, DDark=8,
Surface=7, CornerCol=16 (disabled)
Mouse fields: all cleared (count=0, all records zeroed)
Text variables: all cleared
CHR fonts: all freed and set to Nil
Saved screens: all 10 slots freed
Saved text window / mouse fields: cleared
Clipboard: freed
Line buffer: cleared
Clears the screen after resetting state.

ParseLevel0 '*' (RIP_RESET_WINDOWS) resets text window,
viewport, TextWinSize, and kills all mouse fields. This is
a partial reset — it does NOT reset colors, fonts, or styles.

Procedure ClearScreen
Zeros the entire 640x350 pixel buffer (all pixels to color 0).

Procedure ClearViewport
Zeros only the pixels within the current viewport rectangle.

3.4  Drawing Primitives

Procedure PutPixel (X, Y: SmallInt; Color: Byte)
Set a single pixel. Respects viewport clipping and write mode.
In RGB/RGB32 modes, promotes to RGB via active palette.
RIP command: !|X

Procedure PutPixel (X, Y: SmallInt; RGB: TRIPRGB)
Set a single pixel using 24-bit RGB color. v3.0 overload.
Respects viewport clipping and write mode.

Function GetPixel (X, Y: SmallInt) : Byte
Read a pixel color (indexed). Returns 0 if outside viewport.

Function GetPixelRGB (X, Y: SmallInt) : TRIPRGB
Read a pixel as 24-bit RGB. v3.0. In indexed mode, maps via palette.
Returns (0,0,0) if outside viewport.

Procedure Line (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt)
Bresenham line with line pattern support (dotted, dashed, etc).
Updates current position to (X1, Y1).
RIP command: !|L

Procedure LineTo (X, Y: SmallInt)
Line from current position to (X, Y). BGI extension.

Procedure LineRel (DX, DY: SmallInt)
Line from current position by relative offset. BGI extension.

Procedure Rectangle (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt)
Unfilled rectangle outline in draw color.
RIP command: !|R

Procedure Bar (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt)
Filled rectangle using current fill color and fill pattern.
All 12 BGI patterns supported plus user-defined 8x8.
RIP command: !|B

Procedure Bar3D (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt; Depth: SmallInt; Top: Boolean)
3D bar with perspective edges. BGI extension.

Procedure Circle (XC, YC, Radius: SmallInt)
Circle using midpoint algorithm. RIP command: !|C

Procedure Ellipse (XC, YC: SmallInt; StartAng, EndAng, XR, YR: SmallInt)
Full ellipse (0-360) or elliptical arc.
RIP commands: !|O (oval), !|V (oval arc)

Procedure FillEllipse (XC, YC, XR, YR: SmallInt)
Filled ellipse using horizontal scanlines.
RIP command: !|o

Procedure Arc (XC, YC: SmallInt; StartAng, EndAng, Radius: SmallInt)
Circular arc. Angles counter-clockwise from 3 o'clock.
RIP command: !|A

Procedure PieSlice (XC, YC: SmallInt; StartAng, EndAng, Radius: SmallInt)
Circular pie slice (arc + two radial lines).
RIP command: !|I

Procedure Sector (XC, YC: SmallInt; StartAng, EndAng, XR, YR: SmallInt)
Elliptical pie slice. RIP command: !|i

Procedure DrawBezier (X0,Y0,X1,Y1,X2,Y2,X3,Y3: SmallInt; Count: SmallInt)
Cubic Bezier through 4 control points. Count = segments (default 20).
RIP command: !|Z

Procedure DrawPoly (NumPoints: Integer; Var PolyPoints)
Closed polygon outline. PolyPoints = array of TRIPPoint.
RIP command: !|P

Procedure FillPoly (NumPoints: Integer; Var PolyPoints)
Filled polygon using scanline intersection algorithm.
Handles convex and concave shapes.
RIP command: !|p

Procedure FloodFill (X, Y: SmallInt; Border: Byte)
Flood fill from seed point. Stops at Border color.
Stack-based, 4096 depth. RIP command: !|F

3.5  Text Output

Procedure OutTextXY (X, Y: SmallInt; S: String)
Draw text at (X,Y). Expands $VARNAME$ text variables via ExpandVars
before rendering. If a CHR font is loaded for the current font
number, uses vector stroke rendering. Otherwise uses 8x8 CP437
bitmap font. RIP command: !|@

The engine's ParseLevel0 handler for '@' calls OutTextXY directly,
ensuring all text rendered by RIP commands gets variable expansion
and CHR font support.

Procedure OutText (S: String)
Draw text at current position. Same variable expansion and font
selection as OutTextXY. RIP command: !|T

ParseLevel0 'T' and ParseLevel1 't' (region text) both route
through OutText/OutTextXY. This means text variables like $CURX$,
$DATE$, user-defined variables, etc. are expanded automatically
in all text rendering paths.

Procedure DrawTextCHR (X, Y: SmallInt; S: String; AFont, ASize: Byte)
Render text using a specific loaded CHR vector font at the given
scale. AFont = font slot (1-10), ASize = magnification (1+).
Each character is rendered as a series of move/draw stroke commands.
Does NOT expand variables — called after expansion by OutText.

3.6  Position

Procedure MoveTo (X, Y: SmallInt)      — Set current position. RIP: !|g, !|m
Procedure MoveRel (DX, DY: SmallInt)   — Offset current position.
Function GetX : SmallInt               — Return current X.
Function GetY : SmallInt               — Return current Y.

3.7  Color and Palette

Procedure SetColor (Color: Byte)              — Set draw color (0-15). RIP: !|c
Function GetColor : Byte                      — Return current draw color.
Procedure SetBkColor (Color: Byte)            — Set background (palette[0]).
Function GetBkColor : Byte                    — Return background color.
Procedure SetPalette (Index, Color: Byte)     — Set one palette entry. RIP: !|a
Procedure SetAllPalette (Var Pal: TRIPPalette) — Replace all 16 entries. RIP: !|Q
Procedure GetPalette (Var Pal: TRIPPalette)   — Copy current palette out.

3.8  Fill Settings

Procedure SetFillStyle (Style: Word; Color: Byte)
Set fill pattern (0-12) and color. RIP: !|S

Procedure SetFillPattern (Var Pattern: TRIPFillPattern; Color: Byte)
Set user-defined 8x8 fill pattern. Auto-sets style to USER.
RIP: !|s

Procedure GetFillSettings (Var Style: Word; Var Color: Byte)

3.9  Line Settings

Procedure SetLineStyle (Style, Pattern, Thick: Word)
Set line style (0-4), user pattern (16-bit), thickness.
RIP: !|=

Procedure GetLineSettings (Var Style, Pattern, Thick: Word)

3.10  Write Mode / Text Style / Viewport

Procedure SetWriteMode (Mode: Byte)            — COPY or XOR. RIP: !|W
Function GetWriteMode : Byte
Procedure SetTextStyle (Font, Direction, CharSize: Word)  — RIP: !|Y
Procedure SetTextJustify (Horiz, Vert: Word)
Procedure SetViewPort (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt; Clip: Boolean) — RIP: !|v
Procedure GetViewPort (Var X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt)
Procedure SetTextWindow (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt; Size: Byte) — RIP: !|w

3.11  Mouse Fields

Function AddMouseField (X0,Y0,X1,Y1: SmallInt; HostCmd,Text: String) : Integer
Register a clickable region. Returns index (1-128) or 0 if full.
RIP: !|1M

Procedure KillMouseField (Index: Integer)   — Deactivate one. RIP: !|1K
Procedure KillAllMouseFields                — Deactivate all. RIP: !|1K
Function FindMouseField (X, Y: SmallInt) : Integer — Hit test (top-down).
Function GetMouseCount : Integer
Function GetMouseField (Index: Integer) : TRIPMouseField

3.12  Buttons

Procedure SetButtonStyle (Var Style: TRIPButtonStyle)
Set button appearance for DrawButton/DrawButtonEx. RIP: !|1B

TRIPButtonStyle fields:
Width, Height   Button dimensions (used by some callers)
Orient          0=horizontal, 1=vertical
Flags           Bit flags: $0002=radio, $0004=checkbox, $0008=init selected
BevelSize       Bevel thickness in pixels (1 = single-pixel bevel)
DFore           Label text foreground color
DBack           Label text background color
BRight          Bevel highlight color (top-left edges)
DDark           Bevel shadow color (bottom-right edges)
Surface         Button face fill color
GrpID           Radio button group ID (0-255)
Flags2          Additional flags
ULineCol        Underline color for hotkey character
CornerCol       Corner pixel color (where bevel edges meet)

Procedure DrawButton (X0,Y0,X1,Y1: SmallInt; Label_,HostCmd: String)
Draw 3D beveled button. Renders:
1. Filled rectangle in Surface color
2. BevelSize-thick highlight lines (BRight) on top and left
3. BevelSize-thick shadow lines (DDark) on bottom and right
4. Corner pixels in CornerCol
5. Centered label text in DFore color (via OutTextXY — uses
CHR vector font if loaded, 8x8 bitmap otherwise)
Auto-registers a mouse field. RIP: !|1U

ParseLevel0 'T' and '@' text commands now route through OutText
and OutTextXY, so text on buttons gets CHR font rendering and
$VARNAME$ expansion automatically.

3.13  Image Operations

Procedure GetImage (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt; Var Buf)
Copy screen region to buffer. Buffer format: width(Word) +
height(Word) + pixel data (one byte per pixel, row-major).
Caller must allocate buffer with ImageSize bytes.
RIP command: !|1C

ParseLevel1 'C' handler allocates a heap clipboard buffer via
GetMem and calls GetImage to capture the region. Any previous
clipboard is freed first.

Procedure PutImage (X, Y: SmallInt; Var Buf; Mode: Byte)
Draw captured image at (X,Y). Reads width/height from buffer
header, then renders pixel data. Mode = write mode (0=copy, 1=XOR).
RIP command: !|1P

ParseLevel1 'P' handler pastes the heap clipboard to screen
if one exists.

Function ImageSize (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt) : LongInt
Calculate buffer size needed for GetImage: (W * H) + 4 bytes
(4 bytes for width + height header).

3.14  Icon Files (BGI GetImage Format)

All icon files (ICN, MSK, HIC) use the Borland BGI GetImage format:

Header:   width-1 (Word) + height-1 (Word)
Data:     4 EGA bit planes interleaved per scanline
Plane order: 3, 2, 1, 0 (MSB first)
Each plane: ceil(width/8) bytes per row
Footer:   2 bytes padding (ignored)

Example: a 22x17 icon has header 21,16 and data = ceil(22/8) * 4 * 17
= 3 * 4 * 17 = 204 bytes + 2 padding = 206 total.

Function LoadIcon (FileName: String; X, Y: SmallInt; Mode: Byte) : Boolean
Load .ICN file and render at (X,Y). Mode = write mode (0=copy, 1=XOR).
Reads BGI header, decodes 4 EGA planes per row, combines plane bits
into 4-bit color index per pixel, calls DrawPixel for each.
Returns False if file not found or header invalid.
RIP command: !|1I

Function SaveIcon (FileName: String; X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt) : Boolean
Save screen region as .ICN file. Writes BGI header (w-1, h-1),
splits each pixel into 4 EGA planes, writes interleaved, adds
2 bytes padding. RIP command: !|1W

3.15  Icon Masks and Highlights (Phase 2)

Function LoadMask (FileName: String; X, Y: SmallInt) : Boolean
Load a .MSK mask file and apply as AND transparency mask.
Same BGI GetImage format as ICN. Where all 4 planes are zero
(mask value = 0), the corresponding screen pixel is cleared to
color 0 (transparent). Where any plane bit is set (mask > 0),
the pixel is left unchanged (opaque).

Usage: draw icon first, then apply mask to punch out transparent
areas. The mask file must be the same dimensions as the icon.

MSK files in RIPterm154: BUBBLE.MSK, CHROME.MSK, MOUSE.MSK, TANK.MSK

Function LoadIconMasked (IconFile, MaskFile: String; X, Y: SmallInt) : Boolean
Convenience: loads icon at (X,Y) then applies mask on top.
Internally calls LoadIcon followed by LoadMask.
Returns False if icon file fails to load.

Function LoadHotIcon (FileName: String; X, Y: SmallInt) : Boolean
Load a .HIC highlighted icon file. Same BGI GetImage format.
Used for button hover/selected states — the HIC replaces the
normal ICN when the button is selected or the mouse hovers.

HIC files in RIPterm154: BUTTON.HIC, RADIO.HIC, RADIOBUT.HIC

3.16  Buttons (Phase 2 Enhancements)

Procedure SetButtonStyle (Var Style: TRIPButtonStyle)
Set button appearance for DrawButton/DrawButtonEx. RIP: !|1B

Procedure DrawButton (X0,Y0,X1,Y1: SmallInt; Label_, HostCmd: String)
Draw 3D beveled button. Centers label text via OutTextXY (uses
CHR vector font if loaded). Auto-registers mouse
field. RIP: !|1U

Procedure DrawButtonEx (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt;
Label_, HostCmd, IconFile, HotIconFile: String;
IsRadio, IsCheckbox, InitSelected: Boolean)

Full-featured button creation with icon and state support.

IconFile:       Normal icon displayed on the button face.
If empty, label text is drawn via OutTextXY
(CHR font if loaded, 8x8 bitmap otherwise).
HotIconFile:    Highlighted icon shown when button is selected.
If empty, InvertRegion is used instead.
IsRadio:        Radio button — only one can be selected per group.
Group determined by BtnStyle.GrpID.
IsCheckbox:     Checkbox — toggles on each click.
InitSelected:   If True, button starts in selected state
(hot icon shown or region inverted on creation).

Registers a TRIPMouseField with IsButton=True and the appropriate
state flags. The mouse field tracks Selected state for subsequent
ClickButton calls.

Procedure ClickButton (Index: Integer)
Simulate a click on button at mouse field Index.

Radio button:   Deselects all other buttons in the same GroupID.
Selects this button. Swaps to hot icon if available,
otherwise XOR inverts the region.

Checkbox:       Toggles Selected state. Swaps between normal icon
and hot icon, or XOR inverts/un-inverts.

Plain button:   XOR inverts the region (visual click feedback).

Does nothing if Index is out of range, inactive, or not a button.

Procedure InvertRegion (X0, Y0, X1, Y1: SmallInt)
XOR all pixels in the rectangle with $0F. Inverts all 4 color
bits, effectively flipping each color to its complement
(0<->15, 1<->14, etc). Used for button click feedback and
the INVERT flag in mouse regions.

TRIPMouseField (expanded for Phase 2 and 5):
Active        Boolean     Field is active
X0, Y0        SmallInt    Top-left corner
X1, Y1        SmallInt    Bottom-right corner
HostCmd       String[80]  Command sent to host on click
Text          String[80]  Status bar text
Invert        Boolean     Invert region on click
IsButton      Boolean     This is a button (not just a region)
IsRadio       Boolean     Radio button (one per group)
IsCheckbox    Boolean     Checkbox (toggle)
GroupID       Byte        Button group for radio buttons
Selected      Boolean     Currently selected/checked
IconFile      String[80]  Normal icon filename
HotIconFile   String[80]  Highlighted/selected icon filename
HotKey        Char        Keyboard shortcut (Phase 5)
TabIndex      Integer     Tab navigation order (Phase 5, 0=not tabbable)

3.17  Button Hotkeys and Tab Navigation (Phase 5)

Public Data:
HotKeysEnabled : Boolean  — button hotkeys active (default True)
TabEnabled     : Boolean  — tab navigation active (default True)
Text variable: $HKEYON$/$HKEYOFF$ toggle HotKeysEnabled
Text variable: $TABON$/$TABOFF$ toggle TabEnabled

Function FindButtonByHotkey (Key: Char) : Integer
Find first active button whose HotKey matches Key.
Case-insensitive comparison. Returns mouse field index
(1-based) or 0 if not found. Returns 0 if HotKeysEnabled
is False.

Hotkeys are set two ways:
1. Auto-parsed from label: (M) or [F] patterns -> hotkey = M or F
2. RIP command: !|1U hotkey param (2-digit MegaNum ASCII code)
overrides label-based detection.

DrawButtonEx also draws an underline under the hotkey character
in BtnStyle.ULineCol color (if < 16 and no icon).

Function GetNextTabField : Integer
Find next tabbable field after current FocusedField.
Searches forward, wraps to first field. Returns 0 if
TabEnabled is False or no tabbable fields exist.

Function GetPrevTabField : Integer
Find previous tabbable field. Searches backward, wraps to last.

Procedure FocusField (Index: Integer)
Set focus to mouse field Index. Unfocuses previous field first.
Highlights the field by XOR-inverting its region.

Procedure UnfocusField
Remove focus from current field. Un-inverts the region.

Function GetFocusedField : Integer
Returns currently focused field index (0 = none).

KillAllMouseFields resets NextTabIndex and FocusedField.
ResetWindows ('*') calls KillAllMouseFields.

ResolveVar returns current state for mode queries:
$HKEYON$ -> "YES" if hotkeys enabled, "NO" if not
$TABON$  -> "YES" if tab enabled, "NO" if not

3.18  CHR Vector Fonts

Function LoadCHR (AFontNum: Byte; FileName: String) : Boolean
Load Borland BGI .CHR file into font slot AFontNum (1-10).
Parses: PK header, 0x1A marker, binary prefix, '+' signature,
offset table (nchars*2), width table (nchars*1), stroke data
(2 bytes per command: 7-bit signed X/Y, 2-bit opcode).
Returns True on success.

Procedure DrawTextCHR (X, Y: SmallInt; S: String; AFont, ASize: Byte)
Render text with loaded CHR font. Walks stroke commands per
character: Op=1 moves pen, Op=2 draws line, Op=0 ends char.
ASize scales all coordinates.

3.19  System Font Modes (Phase 6)

RIPterm v1.54 supports 5 system text modes, selected via the
TextWinSize parameter of SetTextWindow (RIP command !|w).

Mode  Cols  Rows  Font     Pixels
0    80    43   8x8      Default EGA mode
1    80    25   8x14     Standard VGA text
2    40    25   16x14    Double-width (each pixel drawn twice)
3    91    43   7x8      Narrow columns
4    91    25   7x14     Narrow tall

Font data files:
rip_font8x8.inc  — 2048 bytes, 256 chars, CP437 8x8 VGA ROM
rip_font8x14.inc — 3584 bytes, 256 chars, CP437 8x14
(derived from 8x8: 3 blank rows top, 8 glyph rows, 3 bottom)

DrawText8x8 selects the font based on TextWinSize:
- Modes 0, 3: use Font8x8 data, CharW pixels wide
- Modes 1, 2, 4: use Font8x14 data, CharH=14
- Mode 2: double-width, each font pixel drawn as 2 screen pixels
- Modes 3, 4: 7 of 8 font columns rendered (narrow)

Function GetSysFontW : Integer
Character width in pixels for current mode:
Mode 0: 8, Mode 1: 8, Mode 2: 16, Mode 3: 7, Mode 4: 7

Function GetSysFontH : Integer
Character height in pixels:
Modes 0, 3: 8.  Modes 1, 2, 4: 14.

Function GetSysCols : Integer
Text columns for current mode:
Modes 0, 1: 80.  Mode 2: 40.  Modes 3, 4: 91.

Function GetSysRows : Integer
Text rows for current mode:
Modes 0, 3: 43.  Modes 1, 2, 4: 25.

All text rendering paths use GetSysFontW/H:
- DrawText8x8: selects font table and character dimensions
- DrawButton/DrawButtonEx: label centering
- DrawButtonEx: hotkey underline position
- ParseLevel1 't' (region text): CurY line advance
- ResolveVar $TWFONT$: returns TextWinSize (mode number)

3.20  Scene / Export

Function LoadScene (FileName: String) : Boolean
Load and process a .RIP scene file. Reads each line and passes
it through ProcessLine. Returns False if file not found.
RIP command: !|1R

Function SaveScene (FileName: String) : Boolean
Serialize current screen to a .RIP file. Writes:
1. !|* (reset windows)
2. !|e (clear screen)
3. !|Q... (palette, 16 colors in MegaNum)
4. !|c.. + !|X.... for each non-black pixel
Groups same-color pixels to minimize color change commands.
Returns False if file cannot be created.
Note: produces large files for complex screens — use SaveBMP
for archival when .RIP format is not required.

Function SaveBMP (FileName: String) : Boolean
Export entire 640x350 canvas as 24-bit BMP file.
Maps 4-bit EGA palette indices to 24-bit RGB via EGA_RGB table.

3.21  Image Loading (Phase 4)

Function LoadPCX (FileName: String; X, Y: SmallInt) : Boolean
Load a 16-color EGA PCX file and render at (X,Y).

Supported format:
Manufacturer: 0x0A (ZSoft)
Encoding: RLE (type 1)
Bits per pixel: 1
Planes: 4 (= 16 colors)
Max dimensions: 640x350

Decodes RLE-compressed scanlines: if top 2 bits of a byte are set,
lower 6 bits = run count, next byte = repeated value. Otherwise
the byte is a literal pixel value.

Each scanline has 4 planes of BytesPerRow bytes. Planes are combined
into 4-bit color indices the same way as ICN/MSK files.

Tested with RIPTERM.PCX (640x301 EGA splash screen).

Function LoadBMP (FileName: String; X, Y: SmallInt) : Boolean
Load a 4-bit (16-color) or 24-bit BMP file and render at (X,Y).

4-bit mode: reads nibble-packed pixels directly as EGA color indices.
Handles row padding to 4-byte boundaries. Supports bottom-up and
top-down row order.

24-bit mode: reads BGR pixel data and maps each pixel to the nearest
EGA color using Manhattan distance against the EGA_RGB palette table.
This allows importing screenshots or external images into the
640x350 EGA canvas.

Returns False if file format is unsupported or dimensions exceed
640x350.

3.22  Screen State Save/Restore

The RIPterm save/restore system allows complete graphics state to be
preserved and recalled. BBS software uses this to save the screen
before displaying a sub-menu or dialog, then restore it when done.

Procedure SaveScreen (Slot: Byte)
Save the entire 640x350 pixel buffer to a memory slot (0-9).
Allocates 224,000 bytes on the heap per slot. If the slot already
contains a saved screen, it is overwritten.
Text variable: $SAVE$ (slot 0), $SAVE0$ through $SAVE9$

Procedure RestoreScreen (Slot: Byte)
Restore a previously saved screen. The saved data is copied back
to the pixel buffer and the slot is freed. Per RIPterm behavior,
numbered slots (0-9) are deleted after restore. If the slot is
empty, the call is silently ignored.
Text variable: $RESTORE$ (slot 0), $RESTORE0$ through $RESTORE9$

Procedure SaveTextWin
Save the current text window coordinates (X0, Y0, X1, Y1) and
font size. Only one text window state can be saved at a time;
a second call overwrites the first.
Text variable: $STW$

Procedure RestoreTextWin
Restore the previously saved text window state. The saved data
is cleared after restore. If nothing was saved, call is ignored.
Text variable: $RTW$

Procedure SaveMouseAll
Save all active mouse field definitions (up to 128 fields),
the current mouse count, NextTabIndex, and FocusedField.
All Phase 2/5 fields (HotKey, TabIndex, IsRadio, etc) are
preserved via full record copy. Only one mouse state at a time.
Text variable: $SMF$

Procedure RestoreMouseAll
Restore all previously saved mouse fields. Calls UnfocusField
first to remove any current highlight, then restores MouseCount,
NextTabIndex, FocusedField, and all field records. Current fields
are replaced entirely. Saved data is cleared after restore.
Text variable: $RMF$

Procedure SaveClip
Save the current GetImage clipboard to a backup buffer.
If a backup already exists, it is freed first. Saves the
clipboard data, size, and dimensions (ClipW/ClipH).
Text variable: $SCB$

Procedure RestoreClip
Restore the saved clipboard. Frees current clipboard and
replaces it with the backup copy. Clipboard data, size,
and dimensions are all restored.
Text variable: $RCB$

Procedure SaveAll
Shorthand for: SaveScreen(0) + SaveTextWin + SaveClip + SaveMouseAll.
Text variable: $SAVEALL$

Procedure RestoreAll
Shorthand for: RestoreScreen(0) + RestoreTextWin + RestoreClip +
RestoreMouseAll.
Text variable: $RESTOREALL$

Memory Management:
Screen saves are heap-allocated on demand. Each slot = 224KB.
Full set of 10 slots = 2.2MB. Freed on restore or engine Destroy.
Clipboard uses GetMem/FreeMem. All memory cleaned up in Destroy.

Text Variable Quick Reference:
$SAVE$              Save screen to slot 0 (persistent)
$RESTORE$           Restore screen from slot 0 (persistent)
$SAVE0$..$SAVE9$    Save screen to numbered slot
$RESTORE0$..$RESTORE9$  Restore and delete numbered slot
$STW$               Save text window state
$RTW$               Restore text window state
$SCB$               Save clipboard
$RCB$               Restore clipboard
$SMF$               Save mouse field definitions
$RMF$               Restore mouse field definitions
$SAVEALL$           Save all (screen + textwin + clip + mouse)
$RESTOREALL$        Restore all
$RESET$             Full engine reset

3.23  Text Variables

Procedure DefineVar (Name, Value: String; Persist, Required: Boolean)
Define or update a text variable. Name = 1-12 alphanumeric chars.
Value = up to 255 chars. Persist = save to database file.
Required = cannot be left blank by user.
RIP command: !|1D

ParseLevel1 'D' handler parses the full RIP format:
flags(3) res(2) name,size:?question?default

flags:  bit 0 = persist (save to database)
bit 1 = required (cannot be blank)
name:   variable identifier (up to first , or :)
size:   field width (skipped, after comma)
?question?: prompt text shown to user (skipped server-side)
default: value assigned if user provides none

Example: !|1D00100USERNAME,20:?Enter your name?Guest
Defines $USERNAME$ with default value "Guest".

Function GetVar (Name: String) : String
Return value of a user-defined variable, or empty if not found.

Procedure SetVar (Name, Value: String)
Set value of an existing variable, or define a new one.

Function FindVar (Name: String) : Integer
Return variable index (1-based) or 0 if not found.

Procedure KillAllVars
Remove all user-defined variables.

Function SaveVars (FileName: String) : Boolean
Save all persistent variables to a text file. Only variables
with Persist=True are written. Format: one line per variable,
NAME=VALUE. Returns False if file cannot be created.

Function LoadVars (FileName: String) : Boolean
Load variables from a text file (NAME=VALUE format, one per
line). Variables with matching names are updated; new names
are added as persistent variables. Existing variables not in
the file are kept unchanged (merge behavior).
Returns False if file not found.

3.24  Pre-defined Text Variables (Phase 3)

Function ResolveVar (Name: String) : String
Resolve a variable name to its value. Checks built-in variables
first, then user-defined variables. Name should NOT include the
$ delimiters. Returns empty string if not found.

Built-in variables resolved:

System Info:
DATE        Current date (MM/DD/YY)
TIME        Current time (HH:MM:SS)
RUNDATE     Date RIPterm was started
RUNTIME     Time RIPterm was started

Screen State:
CURX        Current X cursor coordinate (as decimal string)
CURY        Current Y cursor coordinate (as decimal string)
CURSOR      Returns "YES" (cursor always visible server-side)

Text Window:
TWX0        Text window left X
TWY0        Text window top Y
TWX1        Text window right X
TWY1        Text window bottom Y
TWW         Text window width (X1 - X0 + 1)
TWH         Text window height (Y1 - Y0 + 1)
TWWIN       "YES" if text window is non-default, "NO" otherwise
TWFONT      Current system font number

Sound (no-op server-side, but recognized):
ALARM       Alarm sound
PHASER      Descending phaser sound
REVPHASER   Ascending phaser sound

Mode Control (returns current state as YES/NO):
HKEYON      "YES" if hotkeys enabled, "NO" if not
HKEYOFF     "YES" if hotkeys disabled, "NO" if not
TABON       "YES" if tab enabled, "NO" if not
TABOFF      "YES" if tab disabled, "NO" if not
VT102ON     VT-102 mode (no-op server-side)
VT102OFF    VT-102 mode (no-op server-side)
DWAYON      Doorway mode (no-op server-side)
DWAYOFF     Doorway mode (no-op server-side)
CON         Show text cursor (no-op server-side)
COFF        Hide text cursor (no-op server-side)

Action Variables (handled in RIP_Viewer.OnTextCmd):
SAVE, RESTORE, SAVE0..SAVE9, RESTORE0..RESTORE9
STW, RTW, SCB, RCB, SMF, RMF
SAVEALL, RESTOREALL, RESET
HKEYON, HKEYOFF, TABON, TABOFF (toggle engine flags)

Total: 24 value variables + 19 action variables = 43 implemented.
(RIPterm v1.54 spec lists ~103 including client-side variables
like APP0-APP9, sound, and doorway — not applicable server-side.)

Function ExpandVars (S: String) : String
Scan a string for $VARNAME$ patterns and replace each with its
resolved value. Called automatically by OutText and OutTextXY
before rendering. Unrecognized variables are passed through
unchanged. Nested expansion is not supported.

Example: "Hello $CURX$ $CURY$" -> "Hello 100 50"

3.25  File Query

Function FileQuery (FileName: String; Mode: Byte) : TRIPFileQueryResult
Mode 0: existence. Mode 2: existence + size. Mode 3: + date/time.
RIP: !|1F

3.26  Copy Region

Procedure CopyRegion (X0, Y0, X1, Y1, DestY: SmallInt)
Vertical scroll with 8-pixel X boundary alignment.
Overlap-safe copy direction. RIP: !|1G

3.27  Dimensions

Function GetMaxX : SmallInt  — 639
Function GetMaxY : SmallInt  — 349
Function GetWidth : SmallInt — 640
Function GetHeight : SmallInt — 350

3.28  Public Data

Pixels : PRIPPixelBuffer
Pointer to the 640x350 pixel buffer. Access as Pixels^[Y, X].

Clipboard : Pointer   — GetImage capture buffer (public)
ClipSize  : LongInt   — buffer size in bytes
ClipW     : Word      — captured region width
ClipH     : Word      — captured region height

3A. RIP_Viewer (examples/rip/RIP_Viewer.pas — Phase 7)

TRIPViewer extends TRIPParser with event handlers that route all
RIP commands through TRIPEngine. The viewer provides a complete
rendering pipeline: feed RIP data in, get a rendered BMP out.

Usage:
Viewer := TRIPViewer.Create;
Viewer.LoadFonts('path/to/FONTS');
Viewer.SetIconPath('path/to/ICONS');
Viewer.ProcessStr(RIPData);
Viewer.Engine.SaveBMP('output.bmp');
Viewer.Free;

37 event handlers implemented (Phase 7):

Screen:     OnTextWindow, OnViewport, OnResetWindows,
OnEraseWindow, OnEraseView, OnGotoXY, OnHome,
OnEraseEOL
Color:      OnColor, OnSetPalette, OnOnePalette, OnWriteMode
Text:       OnTextCmd ($SAVE$/$RESTORE$/etc action variables,
$HKEYON$/$TABOFF$/etc mode control),
OnTextXY, OnFontStyle, OnMove
Drawing:    OnPixel, OnLine, OnRectangle, OnBar, OnCircle,
OnOval, OnFilledOval, OnArc, OnOvalArc, OnPieSlice,
OnOvalPieSlice, OnBezier, OnFill
Style:      OnLineStyle, OnFillStyle, OnFillPattern
Mouse:      OnMouseRegion, OnKillMouse
Level 1:    OnBeginText, OnRegionText, OnEndText,
OnGetImage, OnPutImage, OnWriteIcon,
OnButtonStyle, OnButton, OnDefine,
OnLoadIcon, OnCopyRegion, OnReadScene,
OnFileQuery, OnNoMore

OnGetImage captures to Engine.Clipboard with ClipW/ClipH.
OnPutImage pastes Engine.Clipboard with write mode.
OnRegionText advances CurY by GetSysFontH.
OnReadScene/OnFileQuery use IconPath prefix.

